      "question": "Show that the product of any three consecutive positive integers is always divisible by $6$.",
      "answer": "Since the product contains at least one multiple of $2$ and one multiple of $3$, their product is divisible by $2 \\times 3 = 6$.",
      "solution": {
        "steps": [
          "Let the three consecutive positive integers be $n$, $n+1$, and $n+2$.",
          "Observe that among any two consecutive integers, one must be even (divisible by $2$).",
          "Observe that among any three consecutive integers, one must be a multiple of $3$.",
          "Since the product $n(n+1)(n+2)$ contains a multiple of $2$ and a multiple of $3$, it must be divisible by $2 \\times 3 = 6$."
        ],
        "derivation": "$P = n(n+1)(n+2) \\\\ \\text{Let } n = 2k \\text{ or } 2k+1 \\Rightarrow \\text{divisible by } 2 \\\\ \\text{Let } n = 3m, 3m+1, \\text{ or } 3m+2 \\Rightarrow \\text{one factor is divisible by } 3 \\\\ P = 6 \\times q, \\text{ where } q \\text{ is an integer.}"
      },
